We further explored the detection of glyphosate residues in the leaves, stems, and roots of the chives, as well as the cultivated soil, that were sprayed with glyphosate periodically over the duration of the experiments (Fig. 6C and D). According to the emission intensity and the equation, the concentration of the glyphosate residue in the leaves of the chives was calculated to be 2.25 μg/g (Table 2
                        ). Comparably, the concentration of glyphosate in the stems and roots of the chives and cultivated soil were measured to be 10.63, 11.36, and 1.65 μg/g, respectively (Table 2). These results demonstrated that glyphosate was in the leaves, stems, and roots of the chives as well as the soil in which the chives were grown. After spraying the chives with glyphosate for 3 days, the amount of glyphosate residue decreased; as the experiment duration progressed, the concentration of the residue gradually decreased, the calculated results of which are summarized in Table 2. After spraying with glyphosate for 10 days, no glyphosate residue was detected in the leaves by our methods, and the concentration of glyphosate residue in the stems, roots, and soil decreased from 10.63 to 1.02 μg/g, from 11.36 to 2.12 μg/g, and from 1.65 to 0.08 μg/g, respectively, indicating that the glyphosate was effectively metabolized in the chives and soil. More importantly, all of the values corresponded well to those measured by HPLC-MS, further corroborating the reliability of the SO4
                        2–-CQDs-based assay for the quantitative analysis of OPs in practical samples.
